## 6.3 Essential Linux Networking Commands

### ping — Test Connectivity

```bash
# Basic ping
ping google.com

# Ping with count limit
ping -c 5 google.com

# Ping with specific packet size
ping -s 1000 google.com

# Ping with interval
ping -i 0.5 google.com
```

**What it shows:** RTT (round-trip time), packet loss, TTL
**Uses ICMP:** Echo Request (type 8) and Echo Reply (type 0)

### traceroute / tracepath — Trace Route to Destination

```bash
# Basic traceroute
traceroute google.com

# Use TCP instead of UDP (bypasses some firewalls)
traceroute -T google.com

# macOS uses traceroute, Linux also has tracepath
tracepath google.com
```

**How it works:** Sends packets with incrementing TTL (1, 2, 3...). Each router returns ICMP Time Exceeded, revealing each hop.

### curl — HTTP Client

```bash
# Basic GET request
curl https://example.com

# Show headers only
curl -I https://example.com

# Show headers + body
curl -v https://example.com

# POST request with data
curl -X POST -d '{"name":"test"}' -H "Content-Type: application/json" https://api.example.com/users

# Follow redirects
curl -L https://example.com

# Download file
curl -O https://example.com/file.pdf

# Show timing information
curl -w "DNS: %{time_namelookup}s\nConnect: %{time_connect}s\nTLS: %{time_appconnect}s\nTotal: %{time_total}s\n" -o /dev/null -s https://example.com
```

### netstat / ss — Network Statistics

```bash
# Show all listening ports
netstat -tlnp    # Linux
netstat -an      # macOS

# Modern replacement: ss (Linux)
ss -tlnp         # TCP listening ports with process info
ss -ulnp         # UDP listening ports
ss -s            # Summary statistics

# Show all connections
ss -ta           # All TCP connections
ss -t state established  # Only established connections
```

### nslookup — DNS Lookup

```bash
# Basic lookup
nslookup google.com

# Query specific record type
nslookup -type=MX google.com
nslookup -type=NS google.com
nslookup -type=AAAA google.com

# Use specific DNS server
nslookup google.com 8.8.8.8
```

### dig — Advanced DNS Lookup

```bash
# Basic query
dig google.com

# Query specific record
dig google.com MX
dig google.com AAAA
dig google.com NS

# Short output
dig +short google.com

# Trace DNS resolution path
dig +trace google.com

# Reverse DNS lookup
dig -x 8.8.8.8

# Query specific DNS server
dig @8.8.8.8 google.com
```

**dig vs nslookup:** `dig` provides more detailed output and supports `+trace` for following the full DNS resolution path.

### ifconfig / ip — Network Interface Configuration

```bash
# Show interfaces (macOS/older Linux)
ifconfig

# Modern Linux equivalent
ip addr show       # Show all interfaces
ip link show       # Show link layer info
ip route show      # Show routing table

# Show specific interface
ifconfig en0       # macOS
ip addr show eth0  # Linux
```

### arp — ARP Table

```bash
# Show ARP cache
arp -a

# Linux modern
ip neigh show
```

### tcpdump — Command-Line Packet Capture

```bash
# Capture all traffic on interface
sudo tcpdump -i eth0

# Capture specific host
sudo tcpdump host 192.168.1.100

# Capture specific port
sudo tcpdump port 80

# Capture and save to file (open in Wireshark)
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -w capture.pcap

# Capture with verbose output
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -v -c 20    # 20 packets, verbose
```

### iptables — Linux Firewall

```bash
# List all rules
sudo iptables -L -n -v

# Block incoming from specific IP
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.1.100 -j DROP

# Allow specific port
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT

# Block all incoming, allow outgoing (basic security)
sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP
sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
```

### route — Routing Table

```bash
# Show routing table
route -n          # Linux
netstat -rn       # macOS

# Modern Linux
ip route show
```

### wget — Download Files

```bash
# Download file
wget https://example.com/file.pdf

# Download entire website (recursive)
wget -r -l 2 https://example.com

# Resume interrupted download
wget -c https://example.com/large-file.iso
```

